<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Afrotropical (excluding Madagascar), Eastern Palaeartic, and Oriental regions (Fig. 322).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
The Afrotropical species of this genus are mainly associated with plants in the families 
<taxonomicName genus="Anacardiaceae" lsidName="Anacardiaceae" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="genus">Anacardiaceae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="Ericaceae" lsidName="Ericaceae" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="genus">Ericaceae</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Jolivet, P" journalOrPublisher="An essay about the relationships between the leaf-beetles and their food-plants. Backhuys Publishers, Leiden" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" title="Host-plants of Chrysomelidae of the World." year="1995">Jolivet and Hawkeswood 1995</bibRefCitation>
; personal data).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
